Theme of the assignment: Lets practice visualization using base R and create cool maps. Load in the Cars93 dataset by running the following code chunk:

library(MASS)
data(Cars93)

The library function will load and attach add-on packages that have been previously installed on your machine. This will give you access to the functions and datasets available in the package. In general, you only need to install a package once (although it may require updating from time to time) but you need to access it using the library command every time you start a new session in R (and want the functionality).

The questions below use the Cars93 data frame as a source of data. This data frame is part of the MASS package and becomes available after loading it. You can get a view of the top of the data frame by using the head command. For more information, type ?Cars93. Lets load Cars93 in,

Base R

Task 1

  1. Create a Frequency table and Relative Frequency table (latter uses percentages) for the variable Type. Make sure to round all digits to 3 digits.
table(Cars93$Type)
## 
## Compact   Large Midsize   Small  Sporty     Van 
##      16      11      22      21      14       9
round(table(Cars93$Type) / 93,3)
## 
## Compact   Large Midsize   Small  Sporty     Van 
##   0.172   0.118   0.237   0.226   0.151   0.097
  1. Create a frequency bar graph for the variable Type. You can have count on the y axis.
barplot(table(Cars93$Type),col = c("red","green","blue","purple","yellow","white"), ylab = "count", xlab = "size",main = "Car Sizes",cex.axis = 1.2, cex.names = 1.2)

  • Your axes should be labeled and legible
  • The bars should be of different colors
  • The plot should include a title using the main argument
  • The names, labels, and axes sizes (cex parameter) should be set to 1.2
  1. Create a pie chart of the variable Type.
pie(table(Cars93$Type), col = c("red","green","blue","purple","yellow","white"), cex = 1.2 ,main = "Car Sizes" )

  • The plot should include a title using the main argument.
  • The names, labels, and axes sizes (cex parameter) should be set to 1.2
  1. What is the mode of the variable Type? Comment. #midsize is the mode of the variable Type.

Task 2

  1. Create a histogram of the variable Horsepower.
hist(Cars93$Horsepower,col = "blue", main = "Car Horsepower", xlab = "Horsepower", ylab = "Frequency", cex = 1.2)

  • Your axes should be labeled
  • The hist body should have a color (your choice, not too dark to obscure lines)
  • The plot should include a title using the main argument
  • The names, labels, and axes sizes should be set to 1.2
  1. Create a second histogram with breaks at 25 HP increments instead of 50.
hist(Cars93$Horsepower,col = "blue", breaks = seq(50,300, 25), main = "Car Horsepower", xlab = "Horsepower", ylab = "Frequency", cex = 1.2)

  • Use the breaks argument to define the classes
  • Other setting should be as in part (a)
  1. Which histogram more closely follows or rule of thumb for the suggested number of classes? Explain.
#The number of bars in the histogram should be approximately equal to the square root of the number of observations, so the square root of 93 is about 9.6. There should be about 9.6 bars in the histogram.

Task 3

  1. What is the type of variable Passengers? (Categorical nominal/ordinal or Numerical discrete/continuous?) What happens if we were to make a histogram for Passengers? What is the problem with this graph?
Cars93$Passengers
##  [1] 5 5 5 6 4 6 6 6 5 6 5 5 5 4 6 7 8 6 2 6 6 6 5 5 6 7 6 4 5 6 4 5 5 4 4 7 5 6
## [39] 4 4 4 4 4 5 5 4 5 5 5 4 6 6 4 5 5 7 2 5 5 4 5 5 5 5 5 7 5 5 5 7 6 4 4 5 4 5
## [77] 6 5 5 4 5 5 4 5 4 5 7 4 7 5 4 5 5
#The type of variable 'passengers' is numerical discrete because there are no decimals. The problem with this graph is that a histogram is not useful in this case because the variable 'passengers' is numerical discrete. In this case it doesn't make sense to use a histogram. 
hist(Cars93$Passengers,col = "blue", main = "Passengers", xlab = "Number of passenger", ylab = "Frequency", cex = 1.2)

  1. Correct the problem in part (a) by creating a more appropriate visualization. Make sure to label your axes, place a title, choose a custom color as in the previous graphs. (Bonus: use factor() with levels option to display x axis values with no observations on the plot.)
factoredPassengers<-factor(Cars93$Passengers,levels = c(2,3,4,5,6,7,8))
barplot(table(factoredPassengers), col = c("red","green","blue","purple","yellow","white","green"), ylab = "frequency of passengers", xlab = "number of passengers",main = "Passengers",cex.axis = 1.2, cex.names = 1.2)

Task 4

  1. Make a histogram of the variable Length (the default breaks are fine). Other aspects of the plot should be as in part (a) in Task 2.
hist(Cars93$Length,col = "blue", main = "Legnth of Cars", xlab = "Car Length", ylab = "Frequency", cex = 1.2)

  1. What is the shape of the distribution? Bell shaped distribution.

  2. Find the mean and median of the variable Length. Do these answers meet your expectations from part (b)?

mean(Cars93$Length)
## [1] 183.2043
median(Cars93$Length)
## [1] 183
#If it is a bell shaped distribution then mean and median should have similar values. In this case they are close to each other so these answers meet my expectations of what they should be.
